---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Ricœur: Narrative Identity and the Dialectic of Selfhood | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Ricœur</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Narrative Identity and the Dialectic of Selfhood
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					Ricœur does not offer a thin slogan about “life as story.” He develops a demanding account of selfhood in which narrative mediates continuity, responsibility, and change.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong> First Ricœur in his own terms, especially the identity distinction developed in <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Oneself as Another</em>. Then the narrowest possible Identity Engineering reading. No framework-first shortcuts.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Narrative Identity</div>
					<p>
						In <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Oneself as Another</em> (1990/1992), Ricœur formulates personal identity in terms of a mediated “who,” not as immediate self-presence. The narrative dimension is central because lives are interpreted through temporally ordered accounts rather than through static properties alone.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						This is why “narrative identity” should be read as a task, not a possession. Emplotment configures heterogeneous events into an intelligible arc, but it remains revisable, contested, and vulnerable to reinterpretation.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · The Dialectic of Idem and Ipse</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core distinction (Ricœur):</strong> <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">idem</em> names sameness (what persists as “the same”), while <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">ipse</em> names selfhood through keeping one’s word, responsibility, and practical constancy through change.
					</div>
					<p>
						Ricœur’s point is not that one pole replaces the other. Identity claims in ordinary life move between them: we rely on continuity markers, yet we also evaluate persons by answerability, promise-keeping, and the coherence of action over time.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Narrative mediation holds this tension without dissolving it. That is the force of the “who?” question in Ricœur: selfhood is neither pure substance nor pure fragmentation.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Ricœur:</strong> identity work is interpretive practice, not only structural description. Narrative is one disciplined way to stabilize orientation across change.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> narrative reconstruction as one practical method for Stem maintenance; idem/ipse as an explicit tension to be managed in longitudinal identity design; and emplotment as a bridge from remembered past to actionable projection.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Narrative as Stem maintenance:</strong> Structured life narration can bind memory, commitment, and intention into a more coherent operating self, especially after discontinuity or role transition.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Idem/ipse as design tension:</strong> Durable identity architecture needs both continuity cues (idem) and accountable authorship (ipse), rather than maximizing one at the expense of the other.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Emplotment as reconfiguration:</strong> Re-ordering key episodes can change practical orientation without denying facts, which makes it relevant for identity recalibration after breakdown or drift.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Capable self and responsibility:</strong> Ricœur’s “capable human being” clarifies that identity language is not only descriptive; it is tied to agency, testimony, and responsibility.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation from nearby anchors:</strong> Compared with Parfit-style reduction arguments, Ricœur emphasizes first-person attestation and ethical continuity. Compared with Heidegger, his focus is less ontological analytic and more hermeneutic mediation through discourse and narrative form.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Interpretive boundary:</strong> this page does not claim Ricœur “proves” any geometric model. It uses his identity distinctions as conceptual constraints for practice-facing identity design.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary (catalog access): Paul Ricœur, <a href="https://openlibrary.org/works/OL2145413W/Oneself_as_another?edition=key%3A/books/OL1699919M" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"><em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Oneself as Another</em></a> (1990/1992), and <a href="https://openlibrary.org/works/OL8018161W/Time_and_Narrative_Volume_1_(Time_Narrative)?edition=key%3A/books/OL9900447M" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"><em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Time and Narrative</em>, Vol. 1</a> (with linked volumes in the same catalog family).
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview (stable archive citation): <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2026/entries/ricoeur/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: “Paul Ricoeur” (Spring 2026 archive)</a>.
						</li>
						<li>
							Research index: <a href="https://www.digitalricoeurportal.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Digital Ricœur Portal</a> (bibliography and searchable corpus references).
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Ricœur serves as the narrative-hermeneutic anchor in the Foundations sequence. He is crucial where identity questions move from abstract persistence criteria to lived interpretation, agency, and responsibility across time.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
